<title>Paper Scout Research Report — 2026-06-16</title>

<p>The 2026-06-15/16 paper drop is dominated by three overlapping bets: using geometric foundation models as robot-policy backbones, rethinking how vision-language-action models are trained so they actually follow language, and turning video generators into real-time interactive world models. This run deep-dives one strong paper from each bet and finds that the headline numbers are mostly defensible—but the reproducible, buildable part is often smaller than the abstract suggests.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> <i>Geometric Action Model</i> is the clearest seed for a buildable idea. It shows how to split a pretrained depth/pose foundation model and insert a lightweight causal world model, producing a 1.4B-parameter policy that runs at ~145 Hz and holds up under camera perturbations.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Geometry as the robot-policy substrate</h1>

<p>Recent VLAs and world-action models operate on 2D pixels or 2D-derived latents; the 3D structure needed for contact-rich manipulation is left implicit. A new line of work is trying to make geometry the native representation instead. The strongest entry this period repurposes a geometric foundation model (GFM) as the policy itself, not merely as a feature extractor.</p>

