<h2>DreamX-World 1.0: A General-Purpose Interactive World Model</h2>
<p>DreamX Team (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.16993">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.16993">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/AMAP-ML/DreamX-World">code</a> · <a href="https://amap-ml.github.io/DreamX_World/">project</a></p>

<p>DreamX-World initializes from Wan2.2-TI2V and progressively adapts it for camera control, memory, events, and autoregressive streaming. The core algorithmic addition is E-PRoPE, an efficient variant of projective positional encoding. Instead of applying PRoPE's camera-aware attention over the full token set, E-PRoPE downsamples spatial tokens by 4× and runs a parallel camera-attention branch, then adds the result back as a residual. The paper reports this cuts latency by ~30% while keeping camera-control score within 0.14 points of full PRoPE.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:dreamx:inference]]</p>

<p>Our inspection of the released inference code confirms the camera branch is implemented (<code>PropeSelfAttention</code> / <code>CausalPropeSelfAttention</code>), but also surfaces a gap: the public autoregressive config sets <code>eprope: false</code>, which selects the full-dim branch (<code>attn_compress=1</code>) rather than the efficient one. Parameter counts derived from the config give ~5.0 B for the base DiT, ~5.3 B with E-PRoPE, and ~6.1 B with full PRoPE. The released model is advertised as 5B, so the checkpoint may override one of these flags, or the public config may not match the published model exactly.</p>

<p>The biggest discrepancy is memory. The paper describes geometry-guided retrieval of non-local memory frames and residual recycling to handle revisits. The released inference code implements only a local rolling KV cache with sink tokens and Block-Relativistic RoPE. There is no code that retrieves earlier frames by camera-pose overlap, packs memory frames into the token sequence, or perturbs conditioning latents for error recycling. Either this mechanism is training-only, folded into weights, or omitted from the public snapshot; in any case it is not auditable.</p>

<p>Event instruction tuning is also prompt-only in the release. The structured per-entity event records described in the paper are not backed by a parser or event module; rich captions in <code>eval.json</code> are fed through the standard text encoder. The training stages that turn Wan2.2 into DreamX-World—camera-aware fine-tuning, memory conditioning, event instruction tuning, DMD distillation, and RL post-training—are absent from the repository. The inference path is clean and runnable, but the quantitative edge over HY-WorldPlay 1.5 and LingBot-World cannot be reproduced from code alone.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting: policies, world models, and the reproducibility gap</h1>

<p>Three patterns emerge across the deep threads. First, <b>language is becoming the universal action interface</b>: GAM conditions its predictor on T5 language tokens, APT conditions actions on Qwen3-VL language tokens, and DreamX/Qwen-RobotWorld treat natural-language prompts as event/action specifications. Second, <b>the boundary between policies and world models is blurring</b>: GAM predicts future geometry and actions in one pass; DreamX predicts future frames conditioned on camera/actions; Qwen-RobotWorld explicitly targets policy training augmentation. Third, <b>the buildable surface is smaller than the abstract</b>: GAM's code is coming soon, DreamX's training pipeline is missing from its release, and Qwen-RobotWorld has no public artifacts yet.</p>

<p>The most honest takeaway is that these are strong research signals, not turnkey systems. GAM gives a concrete architecture for geometry-aware policies; APT gives a reproducible training recipe for language generalization; DreamX gives a usable inference engine for interactive world simulation. What is still missing is the full stack—data engine, training code, and checkpoints—that would let someone outside the authors' lab verify the headline numbers end-to-end.</p>
